The paper presents a framework for planning and control of manipulation primitives, which involves robotics (cs.RO) and machine learning (cs.LG) techniques. The use of differential dynamic programming (DDP) for trajectory planning and control suggests that the paper may also belong to the systems and control (cs.SY) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of stochastic models, which may indicate a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the manipulation primitives involve planar pushing and pivoting, which are tasks that often involve computer vision (cs.CV) techniques.
